<p><b>Lysenkoism</b> was a set of repressive political and social campaigns in science and <a href="/wiki/Agriculture" title="Agriculture">agriculture</a> by the powerful <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Stalin" title="Joseph Stalin">Stalinist</a> director of the <a href="/wiki/Union_of_Soviet_Socialist_Republics" title="Union of Soviet Socialist Republics" class="mw-redirect">Soviet</a> Lenin All-Union Institute of Agricultural Sciences, <a href="/wiki/Trofim_Lysenko" title="Trofim Lysenko">Trofim Denisovich Lysenko</a> and his followers, which began in the late 1920s and formally ended in 1964. <i>Lysenkoism</i>, or <i><b>Lysenko-Michurinism</b></i>, may also denote the biological inheritance principle which Lysenko subscribed to and which derive from theories of the <a href="/wiki/Inheritance_of_acquired_characters" title="Inheritance of acquired characters">heritability of acquired characteristics</a>, a body of <a href="/wiki/Heredity" title="Heredity">biological inheritance</a> theory which departs from <a href="/wiki/Mendelian_inheritance" title="Mendelian inheritance">Mendelism</a> and that Lysenko named <a href="/wiki/Ivan_Vladimirovich_Michurin" title="Ivan Vladimirovich Michurin">"Michurinism"</a>.</p>
